00:54:50.760 --> 00:54:52.890
- That's a good question.

00:54:52.890 --> 00:54:56.060
No, I have not.

00:54:56.060 --> 00:55:00.570
But the review of
The Glass Universe

00:55:00.570 --> 00:55:03.000
that ran in The
Boston Globe started

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:04.950
with a comment
about Larry Summers

00:55:04.950 --> 00:55:09.180
and how if he had only
looked right there at Harvard

00:55:09.180 --> 00:55:14.340
he could have found evidence
against his argument.

00:55:14.340 --> 00:55:15.450
Yes.

00:55:15.450 --> 00:55:17.214
- I think this is
a fitting segue.

00:55:17.214 --> 00:55:17.880
I'm Judy Singer.

00:55:17.880 --> 00:55:21.000
I'm the Vice Provost for Faculty
Development and Diversity.

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:25.320
My office was created in 2005 in
the wake of President Summer's

00:55:25.320 --> 00:55:28.260
comments on women in science.

00:55:28.260 --> 00:55:31.050
And I have a question
about Cecilia Payne

00:55:31.050 --> 00:55:34.080
after she became Cecilia
Payne Gaposchkin.

00:55:34.080 --> 00:55:35.880
So she was actually
the third woman

00:55:35.880 --> 00:55:37.605
tenured at Harvard University.

00:55:37.605 --> 00:55:40.710
So in 1958, she
did receive tenure

00:55:40.710 --> 00:55:43.290
from the Department
of Astronomy.

00:55:43.290 --> 00:55:46.590
But I hope you can
clarify a mystery to me.

00:55:46.590 --> 00:55:51.060
She has been presented to me as
the first dual career retention

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:53.580
case at Harvard University.

00:55:53.580 --> 00:55:56.060
And I'm hoping that you
have some information

00:55:56.060 --> 00:56:00.120
from your research that
according to legend--

00:56:00.120 --> 00:56:02.610
and I'm hoping you can
either corroborate or correct

00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:04.200
my legend--

00:56:04.200 --> 00:56:06.450
that her husband,
and I'm not sure,

00:56:06.450 --> 00:56:11.460
and she were being recruited to,
I believe, Princeton and that,

00:56:11.460 --> 00:56:13.710
quote, "the only
reason Harvard tenured

00:56:13.710 --> 00:56:16.530
her was to retain her husband."

00:56:16.530 --> 00:56:19.080
So I'm hoping you can
refute this story.

00:56:19.080 --> 00:56:21.110
- Yeah, I'm sure
that's not true.

00:56:21.110 --> 00:56:21.610
- Good.

00:56:21.610 --> 00:56:23.466
Do you know what is true?

00:56:23.466 --> 00:56:23.965
- Pardon?

00:56:23.965 --> 00:56:25.690
- Do you know what is true?

00:56:25.690 --> 00:56:29.160
- Well, she met her
husband in Europe.

00:56:29.160 --> 00:56:32.070
She was going to
scientific meetings

00:56:32.070 --> 00:56:35.100
and visiting other
observatories in Europe.

00:56:35.100 --> 00:56:38.370
And he was in truly
desperate circumstances.

00:56:38.370 --> 00:56:41.830
He was Russian but
living in Germany.

00:56:41.830 --> 00:56:44.814
And he was thought
to be a Russian spy,

00:56:44.814 --> 00:56:46.980
but he couldn't go home
because the Russians thought

00:56:46.980 --> 00:56:49.080
he was a German spy.

00:56:49.080 --> 00:56:53.280
And he had gone to
this particular meeting

00:56:53.280 --> 00:56:55.560
knowing that she would
be there and hoping

00:56:55.560 --> 00:56:57.840
that he could find help.

00:56:57.840 --> 00:57:01.170
He expected her to be the
age of Annie Jump Cannon.

00:57:01.170 --> 00:57:04.620
But she turned out to be
a young woman his own age.

00:57:04.620 --> 00:57:11.160
And he gave her a written
summary of his life story

00:57:11.160 --> 00:57:14.160
to that point, his situation.

00:57:14.160 --> 00:57:17.040
He was educated in astronomy.

00:57:17.040 --> 00:57:21.930
And she went back to Harvard
and prevailed on Shapley

00:57:21.930 --> 00:57:23.520
to rescue him.

00:57:23.520 --> 00:57:24.240
And they did.

00:57:24.240 --> 00:57:26.730
And they created a job
for him and brought him

00:57:26.730 --> 00:57:27.799
to this country.

00:57:27.799 --> 00:57:28.840
And then she married him.

00:57:31.760 --> 00:57:35.110
But I think she was
always considered

00:57:35.110 --> 00:57:37.737
the more important scientist.

00:57:37.737 --> 00:57:38.711
- That's fabulous.

00:57:38.711 --> 00:57:41.800
Thank you.

00:57:41.800 --> 00:57:42.300
- Hi.

00:57:42.300 --> 00:57:43.200
I'm Jane Kamensky.

00:57:43.200 --> 00:57:45.900
I'm the faculty director
of the Schlesinger Library.

00:57:45.900 --> 00:57:47.880
I think we should be
reissuing those pins.

00:57:47.880 --> 00:57:50.310
They're fabulous.

00:57:50.310 --> 00:57:53.700
But my question is about
generations in your story.

00:57:53.700 --> 00:57:55.410
It's such an important
part of the book.

00:57:55.410 --> 00:57:59.670
And we can see it so nicely
in the photograph where we've

00:57:59.670 --> 00:58:02.760
got women spanning
several decades

00:58:02.760 --> 00:58:05.760
and several decades of dress
style in that paper doll

00:58:05.760 --> 00:58:06.570
photograph.

00:58:06.570 --> 00:58:08.520
So I wondered if
you could give us

00:58:08.520 --> 00:58:11.640
a kind of thumbnail
sketch of what

00:58:11.640 --> 00:58:14.820
changed in the generations
between the immediate

00:58:14.820 --> 00:58:17.280
post-Civil War period
where your story starts

00:58:17.280 --> 00:58:21.870
and where your story ends, and
maybe what stays the same too.

00:58:21.870 --> 00:58:26.890
Your bending over backwards to
tell a glass half full story,

00:58:26.890 --> 00:58:30.030
and I agree with the
need for inspiration

00:58:30.030 --> 00:58:31.350
from the perspiration.

00:58:31.350 --> 00:58:32.730
But are there
things that you see

00:58:32.730 --> 00:58:36.162
as sort of intractable that
stick across the generations

00:58:36.162 --> 00:58:37.620
that we ought to
be thinking about?

00:58:37.620 --> 00:58:39.510
- Well, the pay
problem certainly

00:58:39.510 --> 00:58:42.000
sticks across the generations.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:43.470
So that's one of them.

00:58:46.650 --> 00:58:52.490
Post-Civil War that was the
beginning of women's colleges.

00:58:52.490 --> 00:58:57.140
Those grew up and those
created a feeder system

00:58:57.140 --> 00:59:00.050
of well-educated
young women who could

00:59:00.050 --> 00:59:03.080
come to the observatory
prepared to do the work here.

00:59:06.744 --> 00:59:12.100
And the fellowships enabled
them to get a grounding here

00:59:12.100 --> 00:59:14.800
and then go get a job
at another observatory.

00:59:14.800 --> 00:59:19.910
So they really
infiltrated observatories

00:59:19.910 --> 00:59:21.020
all over the country.

00:59:21.020 --> 00:59:24.200
And I think the
reason that there

00:59:24.200 --> 00:59:28.040
were women doing computing at
Langley and at Jet Propulsion

00:59:28.040 --> 00:59:31.160
Lab was because of
the Harvard situation,

00:59:31.160 --> 00:59:36.380
that it made that look
normal because it worked.

00:59:36.380 --> 00:59:38.330
Before that, computers
had been men.

00:59:41.110 --> 00:59:43.450
I don't know if I've answered
your question totally,

00:59:43.450 --> 00:59:48.850
but I think we've slid backward.

00:59:48.850 --> 00:59:52.660
The situation here was
unusual and special.

00:59:52.660 --> 00:59:55.810
It wasn't a general
condition of women.

00:59:55.810 --> 00:59:58.270
When Miss Cannon went
to Europe to meetings

00:59:58.270 --> 01:00:02.440
she noted that there were no
women working at Greenwich

01:00:02.440 --> 01:00:04.570
and at the big astronomy
meeting in Germany

01:00:04.570 --> 01:00:08.650
there were no women
attending the lectures.

01:00:08.650 --> 01:00:11.890
They would be at meals, but
they weren't at the lectures.

01:00:11.890 --> 01:00:16.080
And she was alone in the room
as the only woman in the room.

01:00:16.080 --> 01:00:22.630
And so it's not that there were
lots of women astronomers then

01:00:22.630 --> 01:00:24.160
and that it shrank.

01:00:24.160 --> 01:00:28.581
But the ones who had the
opportunity here really got to

01:00:28.581 --> 01:00:29.080
excel.

01:00:34.330 --> 01:00:35.340
- Hello, Ms. Sobel.

01:00:35.340 --> 01:00:36.640
I'm Sam Terry.

01:00:36.640 --> 01:00:38.140
I live in Cambridge.

01:00:38.140 --> 01:00:40.360
And I work in the
performing arts.

01:00:40.360 --> 01:00:46.990
I'm struck by the prose of
your writing and the narrative

01:00:46.990 --> 01:00:49.480
economy that you kind of find.

01:00:49.480 --> 01:00:54.100
I'm curious about your
discovery of the narrative

01:00:54.100 --> 01:00:56.380
amidst the history,
amidst the science,

01:00:56.380 --> 01:01:03.480
and how you're able to allow
it to have momentum the way

01:01:03.480 --> 01:01:07.830
a story will have momentum
being true to the history

01:01:07.830 --> 01:01:10.080
and also keeping
it from flatlining

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:12.624
with anecdotes and whatnot.

01:01:12.624 --> 01:01:15.040
You do it fantastically, so
I'm curious about the process.

01:01:15.040 --> 01:01:15.550
- Thank you.

01:01:15.550 --> 01:01:17.820
Thank you.

01:01:17.820 --> 01:01:22.050
Well, the story is paramount.

01:01:22.050 --> 01:01:27.180
And this was a great
story before I touched it.

01:01:27.180 --> 01:01:32.580
And then the thing that helps me
is to think of someone to tell

01:01:32.580 --> 01:01:34.590
the story to.

01:01:34.590 --> 01:01:40.590
And I think every story
has maybe an ideal voice

01:01:40.590 --> 01:01:42.570
or an ideal audience.

01:01:42.570 --> 01:01:46.350
And the audience I had
in mind for this book

01:01:46.350 --> 01:01:49.470
was my daughter, who
is in her mid '30s

01:01:49.470 --> 01:01:51.630
and not at all
interested in astronomy.

01:01:54.240 --> 01:01:58.470
But she is a very
serious reader.

01:01:58.470 --> 01:02:03.920
And she's interested in
women and women's history.

01:02:03.920 --> 01:02:07.910
And I talk to her
about what I was doing,

01:02:07.910 --> 01:02:10.430
and I could see how
interested she was.

01:02:10.430 --> 01:02:15.800
So I thought if I could
tell it to her, even

01:02:15.800 --> 01:02:18.740
with all that astronomy,
that would be great.

01:02:18.740 --> 01:02:22.040
So that was what I kept in
mind all the way through.

01:02:30.050 --> 01:02:34.589
I felt it was crucial to
talk about the science

01:02:34.589 --> 01:02:36.380
that the women did,
that it would have been

01:02:36.380 --> 01:02:40.010
a disservice to them
just to skip over it,

01:02:40.010 --> 01:02:44.630
even though I knew that
detailing the science

01:02:44.630 --> 01:02:48.500
could well make the
book less popular.

01:02:48.500 --> 01:02:53.420
But people like my daughter say
that the story carried them,

01:02:53.420 --> 01:02:58.040
and they kind of whizzed
through the science parts

01:02:58.040 --> 01:03:00.530
as quickly as possible
and they kind of

01:03:00.530 --> 01:03:04.774
got it enough to have a
sense of what went on.

01:03:04.774 --> 01:03:06.065
Does that answer your question?

01:03:06.065 --> 01:03:06.235
- It does.

01:03:06.235 --> 01:03:08.060
You personify the
science very well.

01:03:08.060 --> 01:03:09.890
So it invigorates that interest.

01:03:09.890 --> 01:03:11.580
Thank you.

01:03:11.580 --> 01:03:16.700
- It's having a person
in mind on the other end

01:03:16.700 --> 01:03:20.240
to always think, am I going
to lose her at this point?

01:03:23.980 --> 01:03:25.190
- Hi.

01:03:25.190 --> 01:03:26.420
My name is Maya Miklos.

01:03:26.420 --> 01:03:29.510
